<dl id="n54132a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54132a">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54132a"> 132(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> tree Asoka flowers when / struck W&apos; foot <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54132a"><li>FW 301.f3 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ln/lexln.htm#n54132a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ln/l39ln.htm#n54132a">1939</a> <a href="../../flex/lg/lexlg.htm#f196">&nbsp;fn196</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54132a">MS BL 47478-351</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:330 <a name="lad13" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#lgd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lg/lgd14.htm#n54132a">Draft: II.2&sect;8.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">(Voici quelques-unes de ce conventions: &laquo;Le ciel et le p&eacute;ch&eacute; sont d&eacute;peints comme noirs; le renomm&eacute;e et la gaiet&eacute;, blanches; la col&eacute;re et la passion, rouges; on parle de lotus et de nymph&eacute;as poussant m&ecirc;me dans les rivi&egrave;res et dans la mer;&hellip;l&apos;oiseau Tchakora boit les rayons de lune,&hellip;<mark>l&apos;arbre A&ccedil;oka fleurit quand une femme le frappe du pied</mark>,&hellip;les fl&egrave;ches de l&apos;Amour percent les c&oelig;urs de jeunes gens et l&apos;ont dit la m&ecirc;me chose des &oelig;illades des femmes,&hellip;leur paons dansent au grondement du tonnerre, &hellip;<font color="green">[etc.]</font>. Bien d&apos;autres conventions po&eacute;tiques encore se trouvent dans de &oelig;uvres de vrais po&egrave;tes.&raquo; <small> Ren&eacute; Daumal, <a name="RDLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RDLP"><cite title="source">Les pouvoirs de la parole</cite></a> (1938) [77-8]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Tradition has it that the Asoka tree flowers when kicked by a woman. Also called the Sita-Ashok, it is a medium-sized evergreen tree with large flame-like scarlet flowers that appear in clusters. Its deep green leaves are copper-coloured when young and hang placidly from the branches. It is considered sacred by Hindus and Buddhists and is a common motif in Indian iconography and literature. It also has medicinal uses. Its botanical name is <i>Saraca indica</i>. </mm> </dd></dl>
